5. A method of detecting a inflammatory bowel disease or autoimmune liver disease of a subject which comprises: 
(a) obtaining a suitable bodily fluid sample from the subject; 
(b) contacting the suitable body fluid of the subject with a nuclear envelope protein of neutrophils and myeloid cells having an apparent molecular weight of about 50,000 Daltons as estimated by SDS-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, an isoelectric point of approximately pH 6.0, and is capable of binding with atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, so as to bind an atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody to the said protein; 
(c) determining the level of atypical p-antineutrophil cyloplasmic antibodies bound by the nuclear envelope protein of neutrophils and myeloid cells having a molecular weight of 50,000 Daltons, an isoelectric point of approximately pH 6.0, and is capable of binding with atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, thereby detecting inflammatory bowel disease or autoimmune liver disease of the subject.

11. The method of claim 10 wherein the immunoassay consists of: 
(a) isolation of neutrophils from human peripheral blood; 
(b) preparation of cytoplasmic and crude nuclear extracts; 
(c) SDS-Polyacrylamide Gel Electrophoresis and Immunoblotting; 
(d) semi-dry western blotting 
(e) immunodetection after preabsorbtion of sera containing ANCA with human IgG; 
(f) two dimensional gel electrophoresis; 
(g) affinity purification of atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies; and 
(h) indirect immunofuorescence microscopy.

14. A method of detecting inflammatory bowel diseases or autoimmune liver diseases of a subject which comprises: 
(a) obtaining a suitable bodily fluid sample from the subject; 
(b) contacting the suitable bodily fluid of the subject to a support having already bound thereto an atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody, so as to bind to a nuclear envelope protein of neutrophils and myeloid cells having an apparent molecular weight of about 50,000 Daltons as estimated by SDS-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis, an isoelectric point of approximately pH 6.0, and is capable of binding with atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies; 
(c) removing unbound bodily fluid from the support, and; 
(d) determining the level of the nuclear envelope protein of neutrophils and myeloid cells having an apparent molecular weight of about 50,000 Daltons as estimated by SDS-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis and an isoelectric point of approximately pH 6.0, said protein capable of binding with atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies, bound by the atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody, thereby detecting inflammatory bowel diseases or autoimmune liver diseases of the subject.

20. The method of claim 19 wherein the immunoassay consists of: 
(a) isolation of neutrophils from human peripheral blood; 
(b) preparation of cytoplasmic and crude nuclear extracts; 
(c) SDS-Polyacrylamide Gel Electrophoresis and Immunoblotting; 
(d) semi-dry western blotting; 
(e) immunodetection after preabsorbtion of sera containing ANCA with human IgG; 
(f) Two dimensional gel electrophoresis; 
(g) affinity purification of atypical p-antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies and; 
(h) indirect immunofuorescence microscopy.
